  "A single filer earns $60,000 taxable income. Using 2024 brackets (10%: $0-$11,600; 12%: $11,601-$47,150; 22%: $47,151+), what is the approximate total federal tax?": "",
  "$6,000": "",
  "~$8,252": "",
  "$12,000": "",
  "$13,200 (22% flat rate)": "",
  "10% on $11,600 = $1,160. 12% on $35,550 ($47,150 - $11,600) = $4,266. 22% on $12,850 ($60,000 - $47,150) = $2,827. Total = $1,160 + $4,266 + $2,827 = $8,253. Effective rate = $8,253/$60,000 = 13.8%.": "",
  "Choosing a $1,000 health insurance deductible costs $400/month in premiums. A $2,500 deductible costs $280/month. Assuming one claim per year, which is cheaper if the claim is $3,000?": "",
  "They cost exactly the same": "",
  "$2,500 deductible plan — total cost $5,860 ($3,360 premiums + $2,500 deductible)": "",
  "$1,000 deductible plan — total cost $5,800 ($4,800 premiums + $1,000 deductible)": "",
  "Neither — skip insurance entirely": "",
  "$1,000 deductible: $400 × 12 + $1,000 = $5,800. $2,500 deductible: $280 × 12 + $2,500 = $5,860. The lower deductible plan is slightly cheaper with a $3,000 claim. But in a year with no claims, the high-deductible plan saves $1,440 in premiums.": "",
  "A food truck has fixed costs of $3,000/month. It sells meals for $12 with variable costs of $4. How many meals must be sold monthly to break even?": "",
  "500 meals": "",
  "375 meals": "",
  "250 meals": "",
  "750 meals": "",
  "Contribution margin = $12 - $4 = $8 per meal. BEP = $3,000 / $8 = 375 meals/month. That is about 13 meals per day (30-day month). Every meal sold beyond 375 earns $8 in profit.": "",
